Problem 1 - Part 1:¶

Find the various numerical information related to these text excerpts and add them to the textdata.csv as new columns with appropriate labels. The target variable "Bradley-Terry_Score"(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bradley%E2%80%93Terry_model) is related to the readability of the text excerpt; use the following links to learn more about various other scores and create new columns ( at least 10) with each text excerpts respective score and add the columns in the data. More information on text statistics are in https://pypi.org/project/textatistic and https://pypi.org/project/textstat/

In [3]:
# Adding new columns to the data set

# Calculate Syllable Count for each row and add it as a new column
text['syllable_count'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.syllable_count)

# Calculate Sentence Count for each row and add it as a new column
text['sentence_count'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.sentence_count)

# Calculate Word Count for each row and add it as a new column
text['word_count'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.lexicon_count) 

# Calculate Difficult Words for each row and add it as a new column
text['difficult_words'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.difficult_words)

# Calculate Flesch Reading Ease score for each row and add it as a new column
text['flesch_reading_ease'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.flesch_reading_ease)

# Calculate Flesch Kincaid grade for each row and add it as a new column
text['flesch_kincaid_grade'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.flesch_kincaid_grade)

# Calculate SMOG index for each row and add it as a new column
text['smog_index'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.smog_index)

# Calculate Gunning Fox index for each row and add it as a new column
text['gunning_fog'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.gunning_fog)

# Calculate Coleman Liau Index for each row and add it as a new column
text['coleman_liau_index'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.coleman_liau_index)

# Calculate Automated Readability Index for each row and add it as a new column
text['automated_readability_index'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.automated_readability_index)

# Calculate Dale Chall Readability score for each row and add it as a new column
text['dale_chall_readability_score'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.dale_chall_readability_score)

# Calculate Linsear Write Formula for each row and add it as a new column
text['linsear_write_formula'] = text['text'].apply(textstat.linsear_write_formula)

# Calculate Text Standard for each row and add it as a new column
text['text_standard'] = text['text'].apply(lambda x: textstat.text_standard(x, float_output=False)[0])

# Looking at Lasso and seeing if there is a better way to determine the select features. 

# Scale the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Create the Lasso model and SelectFromModel
lasso = Lasso(alpha=0.01, random_state=38)
selector = SelectFromModel(lasso)

# Fit the model to the scaled data
selector.fit(X_scaled, y)

# Transform the features to select the important ones
X_selected = selector.transform(X_scaled)

# Split into training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_selected, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=38)

# Get the selected features
selected_features_mask = selector.get_support() 
selected_features = X.columns[selected_features_mask]

# Get the fitted Lasso model and coefficients
lasso_model = selector.estimator_
lasso_coefficients = np.abs(lasso_model.coef_)

# Rank the features based on their absolute coefficients
ranking = np.argsort(lasso_coefficients)[::-1]  # Sort in descending order

# Create a DataFrame to display feature names along with their coefficients
feature_importance_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X.columns[ranking],
    'Coefficient': lasso_coefficients[ranking]
})

# Filter to show only features with coefficients greater than 0.01
non_zero_features_df = feature_importance_df[feature_importance_df['Coefficient'] > 0.01]

# Display the DataFrame of ranked features and their coefficients

In comparing all three feature selection methods, some common themes emerged. For correlation analysis, the feature with the highest positive correlation to Bradly_Terry_Score is flesch_reading_ease, while dale_chall_readability_score has the highest negative correlation. These two features also scored highly in the SelectKBest method, along with difficult_words, smog_index, and gunning_fog.

However, comparing the results of correlation analysis and SelectKBest to those from Lasso reveals some differences. A few features, such as difficult_words, dale_chall_readability_score, and smog_index, consistently rank high across all three methods. Other features, though, vary in importance depending on the selection method.

    'KNeighbors': KNeighborsRegressor(),            
    'SVR': SVR()                                  
}

# Test set sizes to iterate over
test_sizes = [0.2, 0.25, 0.3]

# Iterate over each test size
for test_size in test_sizes:
    # Split into training and test sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=38)

    # Scaling the data
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)  
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

    # Iterate over each model
    for model_name, model in models.items():
        # Train the model on the scaled training set
        model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

        # Predictions on training set
        y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_scaled)

        # Predictions on test set
        y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

        # Mean Absolute Deviation (MAD) for training and test sets
        MAD_train = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)
        MAD_test = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)

        # R^2 for training and test sets
        r2_train = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
        r2_test = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)

        # Cross-validation using MAD
        cv_mad_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train_scaled, y_train, cv=5, scoring=mad_scorer)
        cv_mad_mean = -cv_mad_scores.mean()
        CV_r2 = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

        # Store the results in a dictionary
        results.append({
            'Model': model_name,
            'Test_Size': test_size,
            'Train_MAD': MAD_train,
            'Test_MAD': MAD_test,
            'Train_R2': r2_train,
            'Test_R2': r2_test,
            'CV_MAD_Mean': cv_mad_mean,
            'CV_MAD_Std': cv_mad_scores.std()
        })

# Create a DataFrame to display the metrics
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# Display the metrics sorted by Test R²
metrics_df.sort_values(by='Test_R2', ascending=False)

After reviewing the results of the various models with different test sizes, Bayesian Ridge Regression (BRR) with a 25% test split emerges as the best overall model. This is evident from its lowest Test MAD (Mean Absolute Deviation) and highest Test R², indicating it has the smallest prediction errors and explains the most variance in the Bradly_Terry_Score. Additionally, the model demonstrates strong consistency between training and testing results, showing no signs of overfitting—unlike models such as K-Nearest Neighbors which struggled with overfitting.

Other models, such as ElasticNetCV and RidgeCV, also performed well but were outperformed by BRR in terms of overall metrics. Furthermore, the model's cross-validation results reinforce its robustness, with a low 5-fold CV MAD of 0.435501 and an impressively low standard deviation of 0.009868. This low variance across folds demonstrates the model's ability to generalize well to unseen data, further validating the use of regression in this context.

After analyzing the data, it is clear that regression is a suitable approach for this problem. The results show that models like BRR and ElasticNetCV effectively predict the continuous Bradly_Terry_Score, achieving high R² values (above 0.7) and low MAD values, indicating accurate and consistent predictions. Given the continuous nature of the target variable and the strong performance metrics, regression proves to be a logical and effective method.

Further refinements, such as advanced feature engineering or exploring non-linear models, may further improve performance, but the current regression models already show strong suitability for the task.

Reflection:¶

This was a fun problem to tackle! I initially struggled with getting the TfidfVectorizer to work properly, so I decided to stick with what I could produce using textstat and CountVectorizer, which still resulted in over 26,000 columns. I appreciated the idea of using multiple methods for feature selection, but ultimately, I settled on the Lasso results because it provided a clear cutoff for selecting important features.

One of the challenges I faced was overfitting the Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) model during feature selection. At one point, I had selected over 2,000 features, resulting in an R-squared value close to 0.99. Recognizing the risk of overfitting, I decided to reduce the number of features to achieve more reasonable R-squared values without compromising the model's integrity.

I also encountered difficulties when trying to generate the correlation matrix due to the sheer number of selected features. However, my favorite part of the problem was Part 3, where I was finally able to run the dataset through multiple models. I really enjoy writing the for loops and seeing the results emerge from the code.

I utilized AI primarily for troubleshooting when I encountered errors in my code and for gaining a better understanding of how to interpret MAD (Mean Absolute Deviation) as a metric.

# Split data into features (X) and target variable (y)
X = text_encoded_2[selected_features]
y = text_encoded_2['difficulty_level_encoded']

# Initialize lists to store the metrics
results = []

# Define models
models = {
    "GradientBoosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(),
    "NaiveBayes": GaussianNB(),
    "MLP": MLPClassifier(),
    "AdaBoost": AdaBoostClassifier(),
    "LinearDiscriminantAnalysis": LinearDiscriminantAnalysis(), 
    "LightGBM": LGBMClassifier(verbose=-1), 
    "SVC": SVC(probability=True), 
    "RandomForest": RandomForestClassifier(),
    "KNN": KNeighborsClassifier(),
    "QDA": QuadraticDiscriminantAnalysis()
}

# Test set sizes to iterate over
test_sizes = [0.2, 0.25, 0.3]

# Iterate over each test size
for test_size in test_sizes:
    # Split into training and test sets
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_size, random_state=45)

    # Scaling the data
    scaler = StandardScaler()
    X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)  
    X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

    # Iterate over each model
    for model_name, model in models.items():
        # Train the model on the scaled training set
        model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

        # Predictions on training set
        y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train_scaled)

        # Predictions on test set
        y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled)

        # Accuracy Scores for training and test sets
        train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
        test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred)
        
        # Cross-validation using Accuracy Scores
        cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X_train_scaled, y_train, cv=5, scoring='accuracy')
        cv_accuracy_mean = cv_scores.mean()  
        cv_accuracy_std = cv_scores.std()    

        # Store the results in a dictionary
        results.append({
            'Model': model_name,
            'Test_Size': test_size,
            'Train_Accuracy': train_acc,
            'Test_Accuracy': test_acc,
            'CV_Accuracy_Mean': cv_accuracy_mean,
            'CV_Accuracy_Std': cv_accuracy_std
        })

# Create a DataFrame to display the metrics
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

# Display the metrics sorted by Test Accuracy
metrics_df.sort_values(by='Test_Accuracy', ascending=False, inplace=True)

Reflection:¶

This problem presented some significant challenges, particularly with feature selection and determining the appropriate cutoff value for the Lasso coefficient. Initially, I struggled with balancing the number of features selected. When the Lasso coefficient was too small, the model overfitted due to an excessive number of features. Conversely, increasing the cutoff reduced the number of features but caused the accuracy scores to decline. Ultimately, I selected 767 features, though this still didn’t yield highly accurate classification models.

Throughout the process, I leveraged AI assistance primarily for troubleshooting errors in my code and learning how to reverse the encoding of categorical variables. This was especially helpful in improving the interpretability of the classification report and in understanding the final predictions for new data excerpts. I also explored additional classification models to see if they would outperform my initial choices, but none provided substantial improvements.

# Since I already have the number of words I now need to number of unique words:

# Built a function to find the unique words in the text excerpts.
def unique_word_count(text):
    words = text.split()  # Split the text into individual words
    return len(set(words))  # Return the number of unique words using a set

# Apply new function
text['unique_words'] = text['text'].apply(unique_word_count)

# Caculate the lexical_diversity of the text excerpts
text['lexical_diversity'] = text['word_count'] / text['unique_words']

Business analytics leverages advanced statistical modeling, predictive algorithms, and optimization techniques 
to derive actionable insights from organizational data. Data is sourced from systems like ERP and CRM, then processed 
through data pipelines for cleansing, normalization, and feature engineering. Analysts apply methods such as principal 
component analysis (PCA) and k-means clustering for dimensionality reduction and segmentation, respectively. 
Predictive models, including logistic regression, gradient boosting machines (GBM), and neural networks, 
are deployed for forecasting and classification tasks. Complex optimization techniques, such as mixed-integer linear 
programming (MILP), enhance resource allocation and operational planning. Tools like Python, R, and SQL, 
integrated with BI platforms like Tableau, support dynamic visualizations and scenario analysis, 
driving strategic decision-making.
"""
# Combine original texts and the new excerpt for consistent vectorization
combined_texts = text['text'].tolist() + [new_excerpt]

# Vectorize the combined texts using CountVectorizer
vectorizer = CountVectorizer()
count_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(combined_texts)

# Split the combined count matrix back into original texts and new excerpt
count_text = count_matrix[:-1]  # All but the last row (original texts)
count_new_excerpt = count_matrix[-1]  # Last row (new excerpt)

# Calculate cosine similarity between the new excerpt and all other texts
cosine_similarities = cosine_similarity(count_new_excerpt, count_text) 

# Find the most similar and dissimilar texts
similarity_scores = cosine_similarities.flatten() # Go from 2D array to 1D array
most_similar = similarity_scores.argsort()[-10:][::-1]  # Top 10 most similar
most_dissimilar = similarity_scores.argsort()[:10]  # Top 10 most dissimilar

# Print the results
print('Using Cosine Similarity Below are the Most Similar and Dissimlar the the New Exerpt')
print('')
print('\033[4mFor Reference the New Excerpt:\033[0m')
print(new_excerpt)
print('')

for index in most_similar:
    print(text['text'].iloc[index])
    print('')

print('\n\033[4mTop 10 Most Dissimilar Texts:\033[0m')
for index in most_dissimilar:
    print(text['text'].iloc[index])
    print('')

A tangent galvanometer is an early measuring instrument used for the measurement of electric current. It works by using a compass needle to compare a magnetic field generated by the unknown current to the magnetic field of the Earth. It gets its name from its operating principle, the tangent law of magnetism, which states that the tangent of the angle a compass needle makes is proportional to the ratio of the strengths of the two perpendicular magnetic fields. It was first described by Claude Servais Mathias Pouillet in 1837.
A tangent galvanometer consists of a coil of insulated copper wire wound on a circular non-magnetic frame. The frame is mounted vertically on a horizontal base provided with levelling screws. The coil can be rotated on a vertical axis passing through its center. A compass box is mounted horizontally at the center of a circular scale. It consists of a tiny, powerful magnetic needle pivoted at the center of the coil. The magnetic needle is free to rotate in the horizontal plane. The circular scale is divided into four quadrants.

# Using the Jaccard Similarity coefficient with the Jaccard Score from sklearn.  The Jaccard Score is found by 
# calculating the Intersection of the text divided by the Union of the text. 

# Vectorize the combined texts using CountVectorizer (binary) this uses the combined texts from the previous part 
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(binary=True)
count_matrix_binary = vectorizer.fit_transform(combined_texts)

# Split the combined count matrix back into original texts and new excerpt as an array
count_text = count_matrix_binary[:-1].toarray()  
count_new_excerpt = count_matrix_binary[-1].toarray()  

# Calculate Jaccard Similarity
jaccard_similarities = []
for i in range(count_text.shape[0]):
    jaccard_sim = jaccard_score(count_text[i], count_new_excerpt[0])
    jaccard_similarities.append(jaccard_sim)

# Convert to a NumPy array for easier indexing
jaccard_similarities = np.array(jaccard_similarities)

# Find the most similar and dissimilar texts
most_similar_jaccard = jaccard_similarities.argsort()[-10:][::-1]  # Top 10 most similar

Machine learning is a subfield of computer science that evolved from the study of pattern recognition and computational learning theory in artificial intelligence. In 1959, Arthur Samuel defined machine learning as a "Field of study that gives computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed". Machine learning explores the study and construction of algorithms that can learn from and make predictions on data. Such algorithms operate by building a model from example inputs in order to make data-driven predictions or decisions,:2 rather than following strictly static program instructions.
Machine learning is closely related to (and often overlaps with) computational statistics; a discipline which also focuses in prediction-making through the use of computers. It has strong ties to mathematical optimization, which delivers methods, theory and application domains to the field. Machine learning is employed in a range of computing tasks where designing and programming explicit algorithms is unfeasible. Example applications include spam filtering, optical character recognition (OCR), search engines and computer vision.

Human sleep consists of different stages which can be distinguished by inspecting the recordings of electrical activity from sensors placed on someone's scalp, a method called electroencephalography. While dreams can occur during all sleep stages, we are dreaming most vividly in a sleep stage known as "REM sleep" because of the occurrence of Rapid Eye Movements. During REM sleep, all body muscles (with the exception of the eye muscles, obviously) are paralyzed by neural structures in the brain stem, which prevent us from acting out our dreams. Accordingly, complex movements like sleepwalking normally occur only during non-REM sleep stages. In such cases, a small part of the brain appears to be awake while the rest of the brain is asleep. This seems to be true for sleep talking as well: producing speech requires the planning and execution of rapid sequences of muscle movements, hence it will most likely occur in non-paralyzed, non-REM sleep stages.

Information technology (IT) is the use of computers to store, retrieve, transmit, and manipulate data or information. IT is typically used within the context of business operations as opposed to personal or entertainment technologies. IT is considered to be a subset of information and communications technology (ICT). An information technology system (IT system) is generally an information system, a communications system or, more specifically speaking, a computer system – including all hardware, software and peripheral equipment – operated by a limited group of users.
Humans have been storing, retrieving, manipulating, and communicating information since the Sumerians in Mesopotamia developed writing in about 3000 BC, but the term information technology in its modern sense first appeared in a 1958 article published in the Harvard Business Review; authors Harold J. Leavitt and Thomas L. Whisler commented that "the new technology does not yet have a single established name. We shall call it information technology (IT)." Their definition consists of three categories: techniques for processing, the application of statistical and mathematical methods to decision-making, and the simulation of higher-order thinking through computer programs.

Artificial intelligence (AI) is intelligence exhibited by machines. In computer science, an ideal "intelligent" machine is a flexible rational agent that perceives its environment and takes actions that maximize its chance of success at some goal. Colloquially, the term "artificial intelligence" is applied when a machine mimics "cognitive" functions that humans associate with other human minds, such as "learning" and "problem solving". As machines become increasingly capable, facilities once thought to require intelligence are removed from the definition. For example, optical character recognition is no longer perceived as an exemplar of "artificial intelligence" having become a routine technology. Capabilities still classified as AI include advanced Chess and Go systems and self-driving cars.
AI research is divided into subfields that focus on specific problems or on specific approaches or on the use of a particular tool or towards satisfying particular applications.

Databending (or data bending) is the process of manipulating a media file of a certain format, using software designed to edit files of another format. Distortions in the medium typically occur as a result, and the process either falls under a broader category of, or is frequently employed in glitch art.
The term databending is derived from circuit bending, in which objects such as children's toys, effects pedals and electronic keyboards are deliberately short circuited by bending the circuit board to produce erratic and spontaneous sounds. Like circuit bending, databending involves the (often unpredictable) alteration of its target's behavior. Databending achieves this alteration by manipulating the information within a media file of a certain format, using software designed to edit files of a different format; distortions in the medium typically occur as a result. Many techniques exist, including the use of hex editors to manipulate certain components of a compression algorithm, to comparatively simple methods.

Geology describes the structure of the Earth on and beneath its surface, and the processes that have shaped that structure. It also provides tools to determine the relative and absolute ages of rocks found in a given location, and also to describe the histories of those rocks. By combining these tools, geologists are able to chronicle the geological history of the Earth as a whole, and also to demonstrate the age of the Earth. Geology provides the primary evidence for plate tectonics, the evolutionary history of life, and the Earth's past climates.
Geologists use a wide variety of methods to understand the Earth's structure and evolution, including field work, rock description, geophysical techniques, chemical analysis, physical experiments, and numerical modelling. In practical terms, geology is important for mineral and hydrocarbon exploration and exploitation, evaluating water resources, understanding of natural hazards, the remediation of environmental problems, and providing insights into past climate change. Geology is a major academic discipline, and it plays an important role in geotechnical engineering.

Data visualization or data visualization is viewed by many disciplines as a modern equivalent of visual communication. It involves the creation and study of the visual representation of data, meaning "information that has been abstracted in some schematic form, including attributes or variables for the units of information".
A primary goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and efficiently via statistical graphics, plots and information graphics. Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message. Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence. It makes complex data more accessible, understandable and usable. Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task. Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.

Acceleration is a measure of how fast velocity changes. Acceleration is the change of velocity divided by the change of time. Acceleration is a vector, and therefore includes both a size and a direction. An object was moving north at 10 meters per second. The object speeds up and now is moving north at 15 meters per second. The object has accelerated.
An apple is falling down. It starts falling at 0 meters per second. At the end of the first second, the apple is moving at 9.8 meters per second. The apple has accelerated. At the end of the second second, the apple is moving down at 19.6 meters per second. The apple has accelerated again.
Jane is walking east at 3 kilometers per hour. Jane's velocity does not change. Jane's acceleration is zero.
Tom was walking east at 3 kilometers per hour. Tom turns and walks south at 3 kilometers per hour. Tom has had a nonzero acceleration.
Sally was walking east at 3 kilometers per hour. Sally slows down. After, Sally walks east at 1.5 kilometers per hour. Sally has had a nonzero acceleration.

# Create a list of quotes
quotes = [Henry_Ford, Andrew_Carnegie, Warren_Buffett, Mary_Kay_Ash, Richard_Branson, Jack_Welch]

# Make all the quotes and keywords lowercase
quotes = [quote.lower() for quote in quotes]
keywords = [keyword.lower() for keyword in keywords]

# Remove Duplicates out of the key word list
keywords = list(set(keywords))  

# Vectorize the quotes using CountVectorizer
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(vocabulary=keywords, lowercase=True)
doc_term_matrix = vectorizer.fit_transform(quotes)

# Convert to dense format for SVD
A = doc_term_matrix.toarray()

# Perform SVD
U, Sigma, VT = svd(A)

# Convert Sigma to a diagonal matrix
Sigma = np.diag(Sigma)

# Display results
print("Document-Term Matrix A:")
print(A)
print("\nU matrix:")
print(U)
print("\nSigma matrix:")
print(Sigma)
print("\nV^T matrix:")
print(VT)
